dict.string: Insertion sort iterates, consuming one input element each repetition, and growing a sorted output list.
Each iteration, insertion sort removes one element from the input data, finds the location it belongs within the sorted list, and inserts it there.
It repeats until no input elements remain.
To begin, the first number is considered fully sorted and is placed in the sorted list.
The first number of the remaining list (unsorted list) is taken out,...
and compared to the number to its left.
so "9" is inserted behind "4" in the sorted list.
Again, the first number of the unsorted list, which is "1", is taken out,...
and compared to the number to its left.
"1" is less than "9", so "1" moves to the left of "9".
since "1" is less than "4", "1" is inserted to the left of "4" in the sorted list.
